On your general question:

> I have a general question. Most of the regular people like me are on either a PC or a Mac, and don't use Linux or Unix like typical TeXperts (my impression). How is it that there is not room in the market for an economical user interface like PCTeX, which apparently has crashed as a company?

My impression has been that "most of the regular people on PC or a Mac" would not need the level of sophistication provided by TeX and use an alternative solution (such as MS Office). This is definitely the case in e.g. the life sciences or the humanities.

In the hard sciences / technical writing circles, the developer lifecycle necessitates certain common tools, such as advanced text editors or IDEs. Which then in turn leads to large communities who rely on TeX-oriented plugins in their editors. The "LaTeX Workshop" extension to VSCode for example, first released in 2016, today reports 1.2 million installations:
https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=James-Yu.latex-workshop<https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fmarketplace.visualstudio.com%2Fitems%3FitemName%3DJames-Yu.latex-workshop&data=04%7C01%7Crobert.jantzen%40villanova.edu%7C220389a908f346217c9a08d92064d4a7%7C765a8de5cf9444f09cafae5bf8cfa366%7C0%7C0%7C637576439730817481%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=TaKvsPbysEWVglL8AwvtJOvtQ6hRzK4SvA18EGXZFEw%3D&reserved=0>

Another modern trend is moving away from local installation and relying on web editing services. As the biggest current example, the Overleaf team reported reaching 6 million users in 2020:
https://www.overleaf.com/blog/reaching-six-million-users-in-an-unprecedented-six-months<https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.overleaf.com%2Fblog%2Freaching-six-million-users-in-an-unprecedented-six-months&data=04%7C01%7Crobert.jantzen%40villanova.edu%7C220389a908f346217c9a08d92064d4a7%7C765a8de5cf9444f09cafae5bf8cfa366%7C0%7C0%7C637576439730827442%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=zpWQEQ3jvZi302xu%2FJkpq6dzpRugRNAHE2Qg8W4z1yA%3D&reserved=0>

The cloud-editing paradigm is much preferred exactly by casual users who do not feel interested in learning the intricate details of software installation and "power user" techniques. It is also a paradigm with a clear business model, and a likely trend to continue in the next decade.

Separately, there are actually tens of support tools for TeX that are available for use today, each serving a different subcommunity / technology stack. This (incomplete!) wikipedia article compares 24 of them at the moment:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_TeX_editors<https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FComparison_of_TeX_editors&data=04%7C01%7Crobert.jantzen%40villanova.edu%7C220389a908f346217c9a08d92064d4a7%7C765a8de5cf9444f09cafae5bf8cfa366%7C0%7C0%7C637576439730827442%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=ML9cR4Wtvc4P6RkjMDkO5TgQkOAv57Jq0rCFdk7wv2s%3D&reserved=0>

